[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(11, 12) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Will he not lay hold on it?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—As the reasoning takes the form of an ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "argumentum ad hominem,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is clear that the act was regarded as a lawful one, even by the more rigid scribes. The Talmud discusses the question, but does not decide it. Some casuists solved the problem by a compromise. The sheep was not to be pulled out of the pit till the Sabbath was over, but in the meantime it was lawful to supply it with fodder. In St. Mark and St. Luke the question is given in another form, and without the illustration, which we find in St. Luke, in another connection, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Jesus bids the man with the withered hand stand up in the midst, and then puts the question, “Is it lawful to do good on the Sabbath day or to do evil, to save life or to destroy it?” The alternative thus presented as a dilemma was a practical answer to their casuistry. They would have said, “Leave the man as he is till the Sabbath is over;” and our Lord’s answer is that in that case good would have been left undone, and that not to do good when it lies in our power is practically to do evil.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Matthew 12:11-13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 12:11-13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he said ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That he might show their unreasonableness, and confute them by their own practice: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "What man — that shall have ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Who, if he have but one sheep, that on the sabbath day shall fall into a pit, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and it be in danger of perishing there, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "will not lay hold on it, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. —",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The stress of the question does not lie on supposing a man to have only one sheep, but on one only falling into a pit; and yet, for the comparatively small value of that one, his not scrupling to undertake the labour of helping it out on the sabbath day. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "How much then is a man better than a sheep? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As if he had said, If the regard you have for the life of your cattle leads you to do servile work on the sabbath, for the preservation of a single sheep, charity should much rather induce you to labour for the preservation of a fellow-creature, though the good office is to be done on the sabbath day. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Wherefore it is lawful to do well ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— To save a beast, much more a man, or to perform any of the lovely acts of mercy and charity ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "on the sabbath day. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Our Lord, having spoken as above, according to St. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 3:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "looked round about upon them with anger, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "with a holy indignation at their wickedness, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "being grieved for the hardness of their hearts, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for their stupidity and impenitence, and for that condemnation and ruin which he knew they were thus bringing on themselves, as well as for the pernicious effect which their conduct would have on others. But at the same time that he testified his displeasure at the Pharisees, he relieved and comforted the infirm man, saying to him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Stretch forth thy hand, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and, a divine power accompanying the word, he immediately stretched it out, and, in an instant, it was made sound as the other. The evangelists say no more; but leave their readers to imagine the wonder and astonishment of the numerous spectators, and the joy of the man who had recovered the use of so necessary a member.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "12:9-13 Christ shows that works of mercy are lawful and proper to be done on the Lord's day. There are more ways of doing well upon sabbath days, than by the duties of worship: attending the sick, relieving the poor, helping those who need speedy relief, teaching the young to care for their souls; these are doing good: and these must be done from love and charity, with humility and self-denial, and shall be accepted, Ge 4:7. This, like other cures which Christ wrought, had a spiritual meaning. By nature our hands are withered, and we are unable of ourselves to do any thing that is good. Christ only, by the power of his grace, cures us; he heals the withered hand by putting life into the dead soul, works in us both to will and to do: for, with the command, there is a promise of grace given by the word.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
