  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 11.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Matthew alone on this occasion,  but comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he said unto them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Christ's answer appeals from intellectual and theoretical difficulties to the practical common sense of ordinary morality (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 3:5-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Their own feelings would guide them to help a brute, much more a man. According to the parallel passages, our Lord first set the man in the midst of them, wishing, perhaps, to draw out their sympathy, and only afterwards spoke this verse of censure (see Chrysostom). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "What man shall there be among you, that",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "shall have one sheep.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " One only, and therefore so much the dearer (Meyer). He would feel an interest in it as an animal that he had learned to love; and he would care for it as his property. In Christ's case also there was the love of man as man, and of man as belonging to him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (\"a son or an ox\") the double thought is distributed over two objects; the man Would love his son, and care for his property in the ox. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And if it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "this",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Revised Version) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "fall into a pit on the sabbath day, will he not lay hold on it, and lift it out?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Lightfoot ('Hor. Hebr.') confirms this from the Jerusalem Talmud and Maimonides. Matthew 12:11",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
